originPortalInfo.title: Toompark
originPortalInfo.description:
North-East entrance to the Toompark(Dome Park) which is formed on a former area of embankments around Snell Pond. The pond, which is the only preserved moat once surrounding the city (dug in that section at around 1760ies), got its name after the city gardener Snell whose garden and house were situated at the bank of the moat. In 1903 the Patkuli staircase connecting Toompea with down town was opened. There are diverse wooden plants in Dome Park because of the relief as well as building the park in several parts and at different times. 

Dome Park is the richest in species and sorts of plants in downtown parks. In autumn 2007 there were ca 110 different wooden plants. 

Year-round favourite location for the ducks (and many other birds, including swans during the warmer seasons)  to hang out with.

originPortalInfo.title: Beacon of Hope
originPortalInfo.description: The Beacon of Hope or Thanksgiving Square Beacon is a £300,000 public art metal sculpture by Andy Scott 19.5 metres high constructed in 2007 in Thanksgiving Square in Belfast. As with other public works of art in the island of Ireland the sculpture has been given several nicknames. These include Nuala with the Hula (credited to Gerard Doyle), the Belle on the Ball, the Thing with the Ring or the Angel of Thanksgiving. It is currently the second largest public art sculpture in Belfast, after Rise on Broadway Roundabout.

originPortalInfo.title: Scottish Provident Institution
originPortalInfo.description: The Scottish Provident Institution building was built in sections between 1897 and 1902 with a design by Young & Mackenzie. It is situated on Donegall Square West and takes up around two thirds of the street. Originally intended as an officeblock it also now houses shops and cafés on the ground floor. During the 1920s the Belfast architect St. J. Phillips had a private practice in the building.

originPortalInfo.title: Mémorial de l'abolition de l'esclavage
originPortalInfo.description: Conçu par Krzysztof Wodiczko et Julian Bonder, inauguré le 25 mars 2012, le Mémorial de l'abolition de l'esclavage a été construit en hommage aux victimes de la traite négrière et de l'esclavage. Situé sur le quai de la Fosse, symbole de la vocation maritime de Nantes, face au palais de justice, le Mémorial appelle au souvenir, à travers les 2000 plaques de verre portant le nom des bateaux négriers partis de Nantes et les noms des comptoirs de traite.
